ðŸ”¥ Running shell commands automaticallyðŸŒŸ 1. os.path Module â€” SUPER IMPORTANT!

os.path handles everything related to file paths.
ðŸ”¹ 1ï¸âƒ£ os.path.join() â€“ Safely join paths
import os
path = os.path.join("/var", "log", "nginx")
print(path)

âœ” Works on Windows, Linux, macOS
âœ” Avoids mistakes like missing slashes
ðŸ”¹ 2ï¸âƒ£ os.path.exists() â€“ Check if path exists
os.path.exists("/etc/passwd")

ðŸ”¹ 3ï¸âƒ£ os.path.isfile() / os.path.isdir()
os.path.isfile("file.txt")
os.path.isdir("/var/log")

ðŸ”¹ 4ï¸âƒ£ os.path.abspath() â€“ Get full absolute path
os.path.abspath("test.txt")

ðŸ”¹ 5ï¸âƒ£ os.path.basename() / dirname()
os.path.basename("/etc/nginx/nginx.conf")  # nginx.conf
os.path.dirname("/etc/nginx/nginx.conf")   # /etc/nginx

ðŸŒŸ 2. Difference Between os.system() and subprocess.run()
This is SUPER IMPORTANT for DevOps engineers.
ðŸŸ© os.system()
Simple â€” sends command to the shell.
os.system("ls -l")

âœ” Pros
Easy to use
Works for quick scripts
âŒ Cons
Can't capture output properly
Less secure
Hard to handle errors

ðŸŸ¦ subprocess.run() (Recommended)
More advanced and safer.
import subprocess
result = subprocess.run(["ls", "-l"], capture_output=True, text=True)
print(result.stdout)

âœ” Pros
Capture output
Handle errors
More secure
Recommended for DevOps automation

ðŸ”¥ Always prefer subprocess over os.system().
ðŸŒŸ 3. REAL DEVOPS AUTOMATION SCRIPT
ðŸ’¥ Script: Check Disk Usage â†’ If > 80%, Clean Logs Automatically
import os
import shutil
# Disk usage check
total, used, free = shutil.disk_usage("/")
used_percent = (used / total) * 100
print(f"Disk Used: {used_percent:.2f}%")

# If usage above 80%, delete old log files in /var/log
if used_percent > 80:
    log_dir = "/var/log"
    print("High disk usage! Cleaning old logs...")

    for file in os.listdir(log_dir):
        if file.endswith(".log"):
            file_path = os.path.join(log_dir, file)
            try:
                os.remove(file_path)
                print(f"Deleted: {file_path}")
            except Exception as e:
                print(f"Could not delete {file_path}: {e}")
else:
    print("Disk usage is normal. No log cleanup required.")

ðŸ”¥ This script demonstrates:
âœ” Checking system disk usage
âœ” Evaluating thresholds
âœ” Automated log cleanup
âœ” Path handling
âœ” Safe error handling

This is the kind of script DevOps teams actually use.
